# ============================================================
# GitHub Actions Workflow: Deploy to Azure App Service (Linux)
# Authentication method: OIDC (OpenID Connect) — no passwords
# ============================================================
#
# IMPORTANT — TWO WORKFLOW FILES EXIST IN THIS FOLDER:
#   azure-deploy-oidc.yml            (this file) — uses OIDC, requires App Registration in Azure AD
#   azure-deploy-publish-profile.yml             — uses a Publish Profile secret downloaded from Azure Portal
#
# Only ONE should be active at a time. Having both present means both will
# trigger on every push to main, causing a double deployment.
# Keep the file you want to use. Delete or move the other out of .github/workflows/.
#
# ============================================================
#
# WHAT IS A GITHUB ACTIONS WORKFLOW?
# A workflow is an automated process that runs in response to events (like a
# code push). Each workflow lives in .github/workflows/ and is a YAML file.
# GitHub reads this file and spins up a virtual machine ("runner") to execute
# the steps you define.
#
# WHAT DOES THIS WORKFLOW DO?
# Every time you push to the "main" branch, this workflow:
#   1. Checks out your code onto the GitHub runner machine
#   2. Logs in to Azure using OIDC (no passwords — see below)
#   3. Packages the code as a ZIP file and sends it to your Azure App Service
#   4. Tells Azure which command to use to start the app (startup.sh)
#
# WHY DON'T WE RUN PIP INSTALL HERE?
# We let Azure do the pip install (via Oryx, Azure's Linux build engine) rather
# than bundling a local venv into our ZIP. This keeps the ZIP small. Azure's
# Oryx detects our requirements.txt automatically and installs everything.
# This is controlled by the App Setting SCM_DO_BUILD_DURING_DEPLOYMENT=true
# (set once in the Azure Portal).
#
# HOW OIDC AUTHENTICATION WORKS (replaces the publish profile):
#
#   Old way (publish profile): GitHub stored a secret XML file containing Azure
#   credentials. If that secret leaked, anyone could deploy to your app.
#
#   New way (OIDC — OpenID Connect):
#   1. You pre-configure Azure to trust GitHub Actions from THIS specific
#      repo and branch (done once in Azure Portal — see setup guide).
#   2. At runtime, GitHub generates a short-lived signed JWT token proving
#      "I am a workflow running from branch main of repo X".
#   3. The azure/login step sends that token to Azure.
#   4. Azure verifies it using GitHub's public keys and checks it matches
#      the trusted repo/branch you configured.
#   5. Azure issues a temporary access token (~1 hour) for the deployment.
#      No password ever leaves either system.
#
# LINUX vs WINDOWS DIFFERENCE:
# On Windows, we did not have a startup-command parameter — IIS handled startup
# via web.config. On Linux, there is no IIS, so we must explicitly tell Azure
# which command to run to start our app. We pass it here via startup-command,
# which points to our startup.sh script.
#
# SECRETS (stored in GitHub → Settings → Secrets and Variables → Actions):
#   AZURE_CLIENT_ID       : The "Application (client) ID" of your App Registration
#   AZURE_TENANT_ID       : Your Azure AD "Directory (tenant) ID"
#   AZURE_SUBSCRIPTION_ID : Your Azure Subscription ID
#   AZURE_WEBAPP_NAME     : The name of your Azure Web App (e.g. "my-agent-api")
#
#   Note: No AZURE_WEBAPP_PUBLISH_PROFILE needed anymore.
#
# ============================================================

name: Deploy to Azure App Service (Linux)

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main
  workflow_dispatch:

# PERMISSIONS: what this workflow is allowed to do at the GitHub level.
# By default workflows have no permissions. OIDC requires id-token: write
# so GitHub will generate the signed JWT token for the login step.
# Without it, azure/login will fail before it even contacts Azure.
permissions:
  id-token: write  # Allow requesting an OIDC token from GitHub
  contents: read   # Allow reading the repository (needed by checkout)

jobs:
  deploy:
    # We use ubuntu-latest because our Azure target is also Linux — consistent
    # operating systems help catch environment-specific issues earlier.
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:

      # ----------------------------------------------------------
      # STEP 1: Checkout
      # Downloads your repository's code onto the runner machine.
      # Without this, the runner has no files to work with.
      # ----------------------------------------------------------
      - name: Checkout repository
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      # ----------------------------------------------------------
      # STEP 2: Log in to Azure via OIDC
      #
      # Requests a signed JWT from GitHub, sends it to Azure, and
      # receives back a short-lived session token. All subsequent
      # Azure Actions in this job use that session automatically —
      # no credentials need to be passed to later steps explicitly.
      # ----------------------------------------------------------
      - name: Log in to Azure via OIDC
        uses: azure/login@v2
        with:
          client-id: ${{ secrets.AZURE_CLIENT_ID }}
          tenant-id: ${{ secrets.AZURE_TENANT_ID }}
          subscription-id: ${{ secrets.AZURE_SUBSCRIPTION_ID }}

      # ----------------------------------------------------------
      # STEP 3: Deploy to Azure Web App
      # The azure/webapps-deploy action handles:
      #   - Zipping the entire current directory (your code + startup.sh)
      #   - Authenticating with Azure using the active OIDC session (Step 2)
      #   - Uploading the ZIP to Azure's Kudu deployment engine
      #   - Kudu unpacks the ZIP and runs Oryx to pip-install dependencies
      #   - Azure registers "bash startup.sh" as the process to run
      #
      # The `package: .` means "zip everything in the current directory".
      # ----------------------------------------------------------
      - name: Deploy to Azure Web App
        uses: azure/webapps-deploy@v3
        with:
          app-name: ${{ secrets.AZURE_WEBAPP_NAME }}
          package: .
          startup-command: "bash startup.sh"
